This strategy is known as a short-strangle. This strategy involves the simultaneous selling of call and put options with out-of-the-money strike prices, while still holding the same expiration date.

The position is a short-strangle due to the fact that the investor is selling two out-of-the-money options, with different strike prices, and holding no assets. The risk involved in this strategy is having to pay up outright for the underlying asset, or forfeiting a large capital gain, should the shares price surpass the strike prices sold.

This strategy is profitable if the price of the shares does not move wildly and stays around the current price upon expiration. The investor earns a profit as the options sold expire valueless, while the net total of premiums paid is greater than the premiums collected for sold options.

This strategy is often used when the investor is bullish on the underlying stock, meaning they expect its price to rise.

4. Buy 1 $109 strike price call at $0.6: This position acts as a "ceiling" for the overall strategy, limiting potential losses from a large rise in the stock price.
